 \par
| What if you had forgotten how unique() works and mistakenly thought it returns the\par
| *number* of unique values contained in the object passed to it? Then you might have\par
| incorrectly expected sapply(flags, unique) to return a numeric vector, since each\par
| element of the list returned would contain a single number and sapply() could then\par
| simplify the result to a vector.\par
 \par
...\par
 \par
  |====================                                                          |  25%\par
 \par
| When working interactively (at the prompt), this is not much of a problem, since you\par
| see the result immediately and will quickly recognize your mistake. However, when\par
| working non-interactively (e.g. writing your own functions), a misunderstanding may\par
| go undetected and cause incorrect results later on. Therefore, you may wish to be\par
| more careful and that's where vapply() is useful.\par
 \par
...\par
 \par
  |=======================                                                       |  29%\par
 \par
| Whereas sapply() tries to 'guess' the correct format of the result, vapply() allows\par
| you to specify it explicitly. If the result doesn't match the format you specify,\par
| vapply() will throw an error, causing the operation to stop. This can prevent\par
| significant problems in your code that might be caused by getting unexpected return\par
| values from sapply().\par
 \par
...\par
 \par
  |==========================                                                    |  33%\par
 \par
| Try vapply(flags, unique, numeric(1)), which says that you expect each element of the\par
| result to be a numeric vector of length 1. Since this is NOT actually the case, YOU\par
| WILL GET AN ERROR. Once you get the error, type ok() to continue to the next\par
| question.\par
 \par
> vapply(flags, unique, numeric(1))\par
Error in vapply(flags, unique, numeric(1)) : values must be length 1,\par
 but FUN(X[[1]]) result is length 194\par
> ok()\par
